 Seely, 2nd Baronet|Charles Seely]]\n|votes  = 4,588\n|percentage  = 46.0\n|change  = +4.9\n}}\n{{Election box majority|\n|votes  = 792\n|percentage  = 8.0\n|change  = &minus;9.8\n}}\n{{Election box turnout|\n|votes  = 9,968\n|percentage  = 83.4\n|change  = +10.4\n}}\n{{Election box registered electors|\n|reg. electors = 11,946\n}}\n{{Election box hold with party link|\n|winner = Liberal Party (UK)\n|swing      = &minus;4.9\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n===Elections in the 1880s===\n{{Election box begin |\n|title=[[1886 United Kingdom general election|General election 1886]]: Rushcliffe <ref name=\"craig1885\"/>\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n|party      = Liberal Party (UK)\n|candidate  = [[John Ellis (Liberal politician)|John Ellis]]\n|votes  = 4,784\n|percentage  = 58.9\n|change  = &minus;5.3\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n|party      = Liberal Unionist Party\n|candidate  = George Savile Foljambe<ref>{{cite news|title=Election Expenses in Notts|url=https://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000321/18860806/028/0003|accessdate=10 December 2017|work=[[Nottingham Post|Nottingham Evening Post]]|date=6 August 1886|page=3|via = [[British Newspaper Archive]]|url-access=subscription }}</ref>\n|votes  = 3,337\n|percentage  = 41.1\n|change  = +5.3\n}}\n{{Election box majority|\n|votes  = 1,447\n|percentage  = 17.8\n|change  = &minus;10.6\n}}\n{{Election box turnout|\n|votes  = 8,121\n|percentage  = 73.0\n|change  = &minus;10.1\n}}\n{{Election box registered electors|\n|reg. electors = 11,132\n}}\n{{Election box hold with party link|\n|winner = Liberal Party (UK)\n|swing      = &minus;5.3\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n{{Election box begin |\n|title=[[1885 United Kingdom general election|General election 1885]]: Rushcliffe <ref name=\"craig1885\"/>\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n|party      = Liberal Party (UK)\n|candidate  = [[John Ellis (Liberal politician)|John Ellis]]\n|votes  = 5,944\n|percentage  = 64.2\n|change  = ''N/A''\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n|party      = Conservative Party (UK)\n|candidate  = John Henry Boyer Warner\n|votes  = 3,308\n|percentage  = 35.8\n|change  = ''N/A''\n}}\n{{Election box majority|\n|votes  = 2,636\n|percentage  = 28.4\n|change  = ''N/A''\n}}\n{{Election box turnout|\n|votes  = 9,252\n|percentage  = 83.1\n|change  = ''N/A''\n}}\n{{Election box registered electors|\n|reg. electors = 11,132\n}}\n{{Election box new seat win|\n|winner = Liberal Party (UK)\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of Parliamentary constituencies in Nottinghamshire]]\n\n==Notes and references==\n;Notes \n{{Reflist|group=n}}  \n;References\n{{Reflist|30em}} \n{{S-start}}\n{{S-par|uk}}\n{{S-bef|before=[[Kingston-upon-Thames (UK Parliament constituency)|Kingston-upon-Thames]]}}\n{{S-ttl|title=Constituency represented by the Chancellor of the Exchequer|years=1993\u20131997}}\n{{S-aft|after=[[Dunfermline East (UK Parliament constituency)|Dunfermline East]]}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Manchester Gorton (UK Parliament constituency)|Manchester Gorton]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Constituency represented by the Father of the House|years=2017\u20132019}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Worthing West (UK Parliament constituency)|Worthing West]]}}\n{{End}}\n{{Constituencies in the East Midlands}}\n{{Coord|52.87|-1.09|region:GB|display=title}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rushcliffe (Uk Parliament Constituency)}}\n[[Category:Parliamentary constituencies in Nottinghamshire]]\n[[Category:United Kingdom Parliamentary constituencies established in 1885]]\n[[Category:Rushcliffe]]\n", "name_user": "Littlemonday", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eMembers of Parliament:Completed cell on table", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rushcliffe_(UK_Parliament_constituency)"}
{"title_page": "Lightning GT", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=December 2016}}\n{{Infobox automobile\n| name         = Lightning GT\n| image        = Lightning GT side.jpg\n| manufacturer = [[Lightning Car Company]]\n| production   = 2019\u2013 (planned)\n| assembly     =\n| designer     =Chris Longmore, Drive Design<ref>{{cite web|title=The Hidden Work of Design Consultancies |url=http://www.cardesignnews.com/site/home/whats_new/display/store4/item136017/ |work=Car Design News |accessdate=10 August 2012 |date=13 October 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081115220644/http://www.cardesignnews.com/site/home/whats_new/display/store4/item136017/ |archivedate=15 November 2008 }}</ref> \n| class        = [[Sports car]] \n| body_style   = 2-seat [[coup\u00e9]]\n| platform     =\n| related      =\n| engine       = Two 150 kW onboard (rear mounted) motors\n| transmission = 5.5:1 [[reduction ratio]], [[electronic differential]], [[rear wheel drive]]\n| wheelbase    = {{convert|2590|mm|in|abbr=on|1}}\n| length       = {{convert|4445|mm|in|abbr=on|1}}\n| width        = {{convert|1940|mm|in|abbr=on|1}}\n| height       = {{convert|1200|mm|in|abbr=on|1}}\n| weight       = {{convert|1850|kg|lb|abbr=on|0}}\n|sp = uk\n}}\n\nThe '''Lightning GT''' is a [[Battery electric vehicle|battery-electric]] [[sports car]] under development by the [[Lightning Car Company]], a London-based privately owned and funded business.\n\nThe project was initially unveiled to the public in July 2008 at the [[British International Motor Show]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Lightning strikes Tesla at London motor show|url=http://news.cnet.com/8301-17912_3-9997197-72.html|work=Cnet|accessdate=10 August 2012|date=23 July 2008}}</ref>  with deliveries originally expected in 2009,<ref>{{cite web|title=The green sports car with added vroom-vroom|url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2008/jul/09/travelandtransport.carbonemissions|work=The Guardian|accessdate=10 August 2012|date=9 July 2008}}</ref> but sales to the public have been put back due to a lack of UK funding to the second quarter of 2019 when plans for production will be announced.{{update after|2020|2|27}}\nThe Lightning is believed to be in talks with a major continental partner whose technology will catapult the Lightning from its pioneering EV origins to the present day.{{cn|date=February 2020}}\n\n==Technical details==\n[[File:Lightning GT rear.jpg|thumb|left|Lightning GT at the London Motor Show in 2008 where it won 'Most Impressive Car of Show' in an online MSN poll.]]\nThe car is powered by twin rear-mounted [[synchronous motor]]s, driving through independent [[reduction gearbox]]es under electronic torque control. The powertrain system is sourced from [[MAGTEC]], the leading UK powertrain manufacturer, providing [[rear-wheel drive]] and a peak power output capability of {{Convert|300|kW|PS bhp|0|abbr=on}}. with 4000 Nm of torque available at the wheels.<ref>{{cite web|title=Performance |url=http://www.lightningcarcompany.co.uk/Lightning/_PERFORMANCE.html |work=Lightning Car Company |accessdate=14 April 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150414162052/http://www.lightningcarcompany.co.uk/Lightning/_PERFORMANCE.html |archivedate=14 April 2015 }}</ref>\n\nThe Lightning GT accelerates to {{convert|97|km/h|mph|abbr=on}} in less than 4 seconds and  is geared for over {{cvt|300|km/h|mph|round=5}}. Its body will be made from carbon fibre and the chassis from a honeycomb aluminium  structure. This unique H chassis will also house the battery modules which when integrated add massive torsional and beam strength. Final assembly location has yet to be determined, but will be in the European Union.{{cn|date=February 2020}}\n\nA small amount of the development of the GT was assisted with a grant from the UK Government's [[Technical Strategy Board]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Lightning plans more electric cars|url=http://www.autocar.co.uk/car-news/new-cars/lightning-plans-more-electric-cars|website=Autocar|accessdate=29 July 2014}}</ref> as part of the EEMS Consortium. The Lightning GT development car excelled as a part of this consortium with 100% drivetrain and battery reliability over a full years monitored testing. The GT covered more miles{{when|date=February 2020}} than the rest of the consortium combined.{{cn|date=February 2020}}\n\n===Battery===\nThe standard battery specification includes two 22 [[kWh]] [[Altairnano]] [[Lithium\u2013titanate battery|lithium-titanate]] [[battery pack|battery pack 'string]]s'. The 9&nbsp;kW standard onboard charger can fully recharge the batteries in five hours from a dedicated 32amp wired socket{{clarify|reason=Standard socket for what voltage - this differs between countries|date=November 2017}} or 12 hours from any standard socket.{{clarify|reason=Standard socket for what voltage and amps - this differs between countries|date=November 2017}} An optional on-board charger connected to a suitable dedicated domestic power source can recharge the car from zero in 2.5 hours. A full charge will give the vehicle a 'usable' mixed use range of over {{convert|200|miles|km|abbr=in|0|order=flip}}. Lightning are developing further battery combinations to take the range further on a standard pack.  A range extender option is being developed which will enable significantly longer journeys.\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of electric cars currently available]]\n* [[Tesla Roadster (2008)]]\n* [[Venturi F\u00e9tish]]\n* [[Mercedes-Benz SLS AMG|AMG E-Cell]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Lightning GT}}\n* {{Official website|https://lightninggt.com}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lightning Gt}}\n[[Category:Battery electric cars in development]]\n[[Category:Cars of England]]\n[[Category:Electric sports cars]]\n[[Category:Proposed electric car models]]\n[[Category:Sports cars]]\n[[Category:Coup\u00e9s]]\n[[Category:Cars introduced in 2016]]\n",