/lightning-plans-more-electric-cars|website=Autocar|accessdate=29 July 2014}}</ref> as part of the EEMS Consortium. The Lightning GT development car excelled as a part of this consortium with 100% drivetrain and battery reliability over a full years monitored testing. The GT covered more miles{{when|date=February 2020}} than the rest of the consortium combined.{{cn|date=February 2020}}\n\n===Battery===\nThe standard battery specification includes two 22 [[kWh]] [[Altairnano]] [[Lithium\u2013titanate battery|lithium-titanate]] [[battery pack|battery pack 'string]]s'. The 9&nbsp;kW standard onboard charger can fully recharge the batteries in five hours from a dedicated 32amp wired socket{{clarify|reason=Standard socket for what voltage - this differs between countries|date=November 2017}} or 12 hours from any standard socket.{{clarify|reason=Standard socket for what voltage and amps - this differs between countries|date=November 2017}} An optional on-board charger connected to a suitable dedicated domestic power source can recharge the car from zero in 2.5 hours. A full charge will give the vehicle a 'usable' mixed use range of over {{convert|200|miles|km|abbr=in|0|order=flip}}. Lightning are developing further battery combinations to take the range further on a standard pack.  A range extender option is being developed which will enable significantly longer journeys.\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of electric cars currently available]]\n* [[Tesla Roadster (2008)]]\n* [[Venturi F\u00e9tish]]\n* [[Mercedes-Benz SLS AMG|AMG E-Cell]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Lightning GT}}\n* {{Official website|https://lightningev.com}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lightning Gt}}\n[[Category:Battery electric cars in development]]\n[[Category:Cars of England]]\n[[Category:Electric sports cars]]\n[[Category:Proposed electric car models]]\n[[Category:Sports cars]]\n[[Category:Coup\u00e9s]]\n[[Category:Cars introduced in 2016]]\n", "name_user": "Warren Whyte", 