{"title_page": "Saroj Yadav", "text_new": "{{short description|Indian politician}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2017}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=November 2017}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name          = Saroj Yadav\n| birth_name    = Saroj Yadav\n| caption       = \n| image         = \n| birth_date    = {{Birth date and age|1982|10|4|df=yes}}\n| birth_place   = Keshopur,Badhara [[Arrah]], India\n| residence     = [[Arrah], Bihar\n| death_date    = \n| death_place   = \n| office        = [[Bihar Legislative Assembly|Member of Bihar Legislative Assembly]]\n| constituency  = [[Barhara (Vidhan Sabha constituency)|Barhara]]\n| term_start    = 2015\n| term_end      = incumbent\n| predecessor   = Raghwendra Pratap Singh\n| successor     = incumbent\n| office1       = \n| constituency1 = \n| term1         = \n| term_end1     = \n| predecessor1  = \n| successor1    = \n| office2       = \n| constituency2 = \n| term_start2   = \n| predecessor2  = \n| successor2    = \n| party         = [[Rashtriya Janata Dal]]\n| otherparty    = \n| spouse        = \n| children      = \n| relatives     = Rama Shankar Yadav (father)\n| website       = \n| alma_mater    = [[Veer Kunwar Singh University]]\n| profession    = [[Politician]]\n| date          =  |\n| year          =  |\n| source        = \n}}\n'''Saroj Yadav''' is an Indian politician. He was elected to the [[Bihar Legislative Assembly]] from [[Barhara (Vidhan Sabha constituency)|Barhara]] in [[Arrah]] district of [[Bihar]] in the 2015 Member of [[Bihar Legislative Assembly]] as a member of the [[Rashtriya Janata Dal]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.elections.in/bihar/assembly-constituencies/barhara.html|title= Bihar Legislative Assembly Election 2015|}} </ref>\n\n==Lagislator==\nHe make a historical record in [[Barhara (Vidhan Sabha constituency)|Barhara]] in 2015 [[Bihar Vidhan Sabha]] election,from 1952 election no one won from backward caste as a MLA from this constituency\n\n==Ref==\n* https://www.mapsofindia.com/assemblypolls/bihar/barhara.html\n* http://vidhansabha.bih.nic.in/Knowyourmla.html\n* https://www.jagran.com/bihar/patna-city-criminals-demanded-10-lakh-extortion-on-phone-frome-rjd-mla-saroj-yadav-19570863.html\n* https://betahindi.news18.com/news/bihar/rjd-mla-saroj-yadav-sits-on-death-strike-against-his-own-government-999443.html\n\n\n\n[[Category:People from Arrah]]\n[[Category:Bihar MLAs 2015\u2013]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Rashtriya Janata Dal politicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Indian politician}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{Cleanup|reason=source code issues|date=April 2020}}\n{{Copy edit|for=grammar|date=April 2020}}\n}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name          = Saroj Yadav\n| birth_name    = Saroj Yadav\n| caption       = \n| image         = \n| birth_date    = \n| birth_place   = Keshopur,Badhara [[Ara, Bihar]], India\n| residence     = [[Arrah], Bihar\n| death_date    = \n| death_place   = \n| office        = [[Bihar Legislative Assembly|Member of Bihar Legislative Assembly]]\n| constituency  = [[Barhara (Vidhan Sabha constituency)|Barhara]]\n| term_start    = 2015\n| term_end      = incumbent\n| predecessor   = Raghwendra Pratap Singh\n| successor     = incumbent\n| office1       = \n| constituency1 = \n| term1         = \n| term_end1     = \n| predecessor1  = \n| successor1    = \n| office2       = \n| constituency2 = \n| term_start2   = \n| predecessor2  = \n| successor2    = \n| party         = [[Rashtriya Janata Dal]]\n| otherparty    = \n| spouse        = \n| children      = \n| relatives     = Rama Shankar Yadav (father)\n| website       = \n| alma_mater    = 10th Pass\n| profession    = [[Politician]]\n| date          =  |\n| year          =  |\n| source        = \n}}\n'''Saroj Yadav''' is an Indian politician. He was elected to the [[Bihar Legislative Assembly]] from [[Barhara (Vidhan Sabha constituency)|Barhara]] in [[Arrah]] district of [[Bihar]] in the 2015 Member of [[Bihar Legislative Assembly]] as a member of the [[Rashtriya Janata Dal]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.elections.in/bihar/assembly-constituencies/barhara.html|title= Bihar Legislative Assembly Election 2015|}} </ref>\n\n==Lagislator==\nHe make a historical record in [[Barhara (Vidhan Sabha constituency)|Barhara]] in 2015 [[Bihar Vidhan Sabha]] election,from 1952 election no one won from backward caste as a MLA from this constituency\n\n==Ref==\n* https://www.mapsofindia.com/assemblypolls/bihar/barhara.html\n* http://vidhansabha.bih.nic.in/Knowyourmla.html\n* https://www.jagran.com/bihar/patna-city-criminals-demanded-10-lakh-extortion-on-phone-frome-rjd-mla-saroj-yadav-19570863.html\n* \n\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Saroj Yadav}}\n[[Category:People from Arrah]]\n[[Category:Bihar MLAs 2015\u2013]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Rashtriya Janata Dal politicians]]\n\n{{India-politician-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Vipinahir", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Saroj_Yadav"}
{"title_page": "Maybanke Anderson", "text_new": "{{Use British English|date=August 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2011}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Maybanke Anderson\n| image         = Maybanke Anderson c.1893.png\n| alt           = \n| caption       = Maybanke Anderson, c.1893\n| birth_name    = Maybanke Selfe\n| birth_date     = {{birth date|1845|2|16|df=y}}\n| birth_place    = Kingston upon Thames, United Kingdom\n| death_date     = {{death date and age|1927|4|15|1845|2|16|df=y}}\n| death_place   = Paris, France\n| nationality   = Australian\n| alma_mater    =\n| other_names   = \n| occupation    = Suffragist\n| years_active  = \n| known_for     = \n| notable_works = \n| spouse        = {{plainlist|\n* {{marriage|Edmund Kay Wolstenholme|1867|1893|end=div}}\n* {{marriage|Francis Anderson|1899}}}}\n}}\n\n'''Maybanke Susannah Anderson''', also known as '''Maybanke Wolstenholme''' (16 February 1845 &ndash; 15 April 1927) was a [[Sydney]] reformer involved in [[women's suffrage]] and [[Australian federation|federation]].\n\n==Early life==\n\nMaybanke Anderson n\u00e9e Selfe was born at [[Kingston upon Thames]], United Kingdom, near the city [[London]].<ref>{{Cite AuDB|id2=anderson-maybanke-susannah-5018|title=Anderson, Maybanke Susannah (1845 - 1927)|year=1979|volume=7|first=Beverley|last=Kingston|access-date=2011-02-26}}</ref> She was the sister of [[Norman Selfe]] and a cousin of [[Eadward Muybridge]], who migrated to the United States in 1850. Her family migrated to [[Australia]] as free settlers when she was nine years old. Twelve years later in September 1867 she married Edmund Kay Wolstenholme, a timber merchant. The couple had seven children between 1868 and 1879, four of them died from a heart condition before the age of five. Her son, [[Harry Wolstenholme]], was a [[lawyer]] and keen amateur [[ornithologist]]. The Wolstenholmes built a large house called  'Maybanke' in [[Marrickville, New South Wales|Marrickville]]. The later years of the marriage were unhappy; Edmund had a number of business failures and became an alcoholic, leaving the family in 1884. Maybanke had to wait for the passage of the ''[[Divorce Amendment and Extension Act]]'' in 1892 before she could [[divorce]] Edmund on the grounds of ''\"three years of desertion.\"'' The divorce was finalised in 1893.<ref name=\"Roberts\">{{cite book |title= Maybanke Anderson: SEX, suffrage and social reform|last= Roberts|first=Jan |year= 1993|publisher= Hale & Iremonger|location= Sydney|isbn= 0868064955}} p.37</ref> After the divorce, she was supported financially by her brother, the renowned engineer [[Norman Selfe]], with whom she would later campaign for education reform.{{sfn|Roberts|1993|p=54}}\n\nIn 1885 Maybanke opened Maybanke School, a girls' school that she operated in her home preparing girls for the [[University of Sydney]] entrance examination. Operating for 10 years, the school was later known as Maybanke College.<ref>Nugent, A. 2001. [http://www.nla.gov.au/pub/nlanews/2001/may01/story-4.pdf Maybanke Anderson Feminist, Suffragist and Federationist], National Library of Australia News, Volume XI Number 8. p. 14</ref>\n[[File:(1)Former Methodist Chapel Harris Street Pyrmont.jpg|right|thumb|250px|Maybanke Kindergarten in [[Pyrmont, New South Wales]], named after Anderson]]\n\n==Woman suffrage activist==\nFollowing her divorce, Maybanke took an active role in the promotion of women and children's rights. She became active in the women's suffrage movement; she believed that the vote was 'the kernel for all reform'. She was vice president of the Women's Literary Society started by her friend [[Rose Scott]]. Many of the society's members would go on to form the [[Womanhood Suffrage League of New South Wales]] (WSL) on 6 May 1891.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nla.gov.au/guides/federation/politics.html |title=Federation Political Groups\u2014to 1901 and beyond | accessdate=2011-02-26}}</ref> In 1893 she was elected to the WSL presidency, and founded the Australasian Home Reading Union in the same year. The Union was a program to promote induction by organising small study groups in rural areas.\n\nIn 1894, she began publishing the fortnightly newspaper ''Woman's Voice''. The paper ran for 18 months, drawing women's attention to suffrage issues at the national and international level. In 1895 she established the first free kindergarten in [[Australia]] at [[Woolloomooloo, New South Wales|Woolloomooloo]] as the president of the Kindergarten Union, helping the children of working mothers.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.abc.net.au/rn/hindsight/stories/2009/2656479.htm |title=Gardens for children and workshops for classrooms: Maybanke Anderson, Norman Selfe and the New Education - Hindsight, Radio National 16 August 2009 |accessdate=2011-02-26|date=14 August 2009 }}</ref>\n\nThe WSL's attempts to have suffrage implemented by the New South Wales government were not fruitful; however, in 1897, Maybanke decided to petition the 1897 Federal Convention in [[Adelaide]]. She reasoned that this would have the women's vote written into the Federal agenda. Thus, the women from [[South Australia|South]] and [[Western Australia]] who already had the vote could not have it taken from them, and if there was suffrage at the federal level, it would flow down to the states. At this time, she also became involved in the [[Federation of Australia|pro-federation movement]]. Maybanke resigned from the WSL in 1897. Suffrage was extended to the women of New South Wales in 1902.\n\nMaybanke was inducted onto the [[Victorian Honour Roll of Women]] in 2001 in recognition of her achievements.\n\n==Marriage and travel==\nIn 1899 Maybanke married her second husband, [[Francis Anderson (philosopher)|Sir Francis Anderson]]. Anderson was the first Professor of Philosophy at the [[University of Sydney]]. They travelled and worked together on voluntary projects, including campaigning to have women stand for local government. She was active with the National Council of Women of New South Wales, and worked closely with the University Women's Society.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://trove.nla.gov.au/people/466159 | title=Anderson, Maybanke (1845-1927) - Trove, National Library of Australia |accessdate=2011-02-26}}</ref> Maybanke died in St Germain-en-Laye, Paris on 15 April 1927.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://adb.anu.edu.au/biography/anderson-maybanke-susannah-5018/text8347 Anderson, Maybanke Susannah (1845\u20131927)] in ''Australian Dictionary of Biography''\n* [http://dictionaryofsydney.org/entry/anderson_maybanke Anderson, Maybanke] in ''Dictionary of Sydney''\n* [http://www.womenaustralia.info/leaders/biogs/WLE0601b.htm Anderson, Maybanke Susannah (1845 - 1927)] in ''The Encyclopedia of Women and Leadership in the Twentieth Century''\n\n==Bibliography==\n* Roberts, Jan (1993). ''Maybanke Anderson: Sex, suffrage and social reform''. Sydney: Hale & Iremonger. {{ISBN|0868064955}}.\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Anderson, Maybanke}}\n[[Category:1845 births]]\n[[Category:1927 deaths]]\n[[Category:19th-century Australian people]]\n[[Category:Australian suffragists]]\n[[Category:English emigrants to colonial Australia]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use British English|date=August 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2011}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Maybanke Anderson\n| image         = Maybanke Anderson c.1893.png\n| alt           = \n| caption       = Maybanke Anderson, c.1893\n| birth_name    = Maybanke Selfe\n| birth_date     = {{birth date|1845|2|16|df=y}}\n| birth_place    = Kingston upon Thames, United Kingdom\n| death_date     = {{death date and age|1927|4|15|1845|2|16|df=y}}\n| death_place   = Paris, France\n| nationality   = Australian\n| alma_mater    =\n| other_names   = \n| occupation    = Suffragist\n| years_active  = \n| known_for     = \n| notable_works = \n| spouse        = {{plainlist|\n* {{marriage|Edmund Kay Wolstenholme|1867|1893|end=div}}\n* {{marriage|Francis Anderson|1899}}}}\n}}\n\n'''Maybanke Susannah Anderson''', also known as '''Maybanke Wolstenholme''' (16 February 1845 &ndash; 15 April 1927) was a [[Sydney]] reformer involved in [[women's suffrage]] and [[Australian federation|federation]].\n\n==Early life==\n\nMaybanke Anderson n\u00e9e Selfe was born at [[Kingston upon Thames]], United Kingdom, near the city [[London]].<ref>{{Cite AuDB|id2=anderson-maybanke-susannah-5018|title=Anderson, Maybanke Susannah (1845 - 1927)|year=1979|volume=7=first=Beverley|last=Kingston|access-date=2011-02-26}}</ref> She was the sister of [[Norman Selfe]] and a cousin of [[Eadward Muybridge]], who migrated to the United States in 1850. Her family migrated to [[Australia]] as free settlers when she was nine years old. Twelve years later in September 1867 she married Edmund Kay Wolstenholme, a timber merchant. The couple had seven children between 1868 and 1879, four of them died from a heart condition before the age of five. Her son, [[Harry Wolstenholme]], was a [[lawyer]] and keen amateur [[ornithologist]]. The Wolstenholmes built a large house called  'Maybanke' in [[Marrickville, New South Wales|Marrickville]]. The later years of the marriage were unhappy; Edmund had a number of business failures and became an alcoholic, leaving the family in 1884. Maybanke had to wait for the passage of the ''[[Divorce Amendment and Extension Act]]'' in 1892 before she could [[divorce]] Edmund on the grounds of ''\"three years of desertion.\"'' The divorce was finalised in 1893.<ref name=\"Roberts\">{{cite book |title= Maybanke Anderson: SEX, suffrage and social reform|last= Roberts|first=Jan |year= 1993|publisher= Hale & Iremonger|location= Sydney|isbn= 0868064955}} p.37</ref> After the divorce, she was supported financially by her brother, the renowned engineer [[Norman Selfe]], with whom she would later campaign for education reform.{{sfn|Roberts|1993|p=54}}\n\nIn 1885 Maybanke opened Maybanke School, a girls' school that she operated in her home preparing girls for the [[University of Sydney]] entrance examination. Operating for 10 years, the school was later known as Maybanke College.<ref>Nugent, A. 2001. [http://www.nla.gov.au/pub/nlanews/2001/may01/story-4.pdf Maybanke Anderson Feminist, Suffragist and Federationist], National Library of Australia News, Volume XI Number 8. p. 14</ref>\n[[File:(1)Former Methodist Chapel Harris Street Pyrmont.jpg|right|thumb|250px|Maybanke Kindergarten in [[Pyrmont, New South Wales]], named after Anderson]]\n\n==Woman suffrage activist==\nFollowing her divorce, Maybanke took an active role in the promotion of women and children's rights. She became active in the women's suffrage movement; she believed that the vote was 'the kernel for all reform'. She was vice president of the Women's Literary Society started by her friend [[Rose Scott]]. Many of the society's members would go on to form the [[Womanhood Suffrage League of New South Wales]] (WSL) on 6 May 1891.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nla.gov.au/guides/federation/politics.html |title=Federation Political Groups\u2014to 1901 and beyond | accessdate=2011-02-26}}</ref> In 1893 she was elected to the WSL presidency, and founded the Australasian Home Reading Union in the same year. The Union was a program to promote induction by organising small study groups in rural areas.\n\nIn 1894, she began publishing the fortnightly newspaper ''Woman's Voice''. The paper ran for 18 months, drawing women's attention to suffrage issues at the national and international level. In 1895 she established the first free kindergarten in [[Australia]] at [[Woolloomooloo, New South Wales|Woolloomooloo]] as the president of the Kindergarten Union, helping the children of working mothers.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.abc.net.au/rn/hindsight/stories/2009/2656479.htm |title=Gardens for children and workshops for classrooms: Maybanke Anderson, Norman Selfe and the New Education - Hindsight, Radio National 16 August 2009 |accessdate=2011-02-26|date=14 August 2009 }}</ref>\n\nThe WSL's attempts to have suffrage implemented by the New South Wales government were not fruitful; however, in 1897, Maybanke decided to petition the 1897 Federal Convention in [[Adelaide]]. She reasoned that this would have the women's vote written into the Federal agenda. Thus, the women from [[South Australia|South]] and [[Western Australia]] who already had the vote could not have it taken from them, and if there was suffrage at the federal level, it would flow down to the states. At this time, she also became involved in the [[Federation of Australia|pro-federation movement]]. Maybanke resigned from the WSL in 1897. Suffrage was extended to the women of New South Wales in 1902.\n\nMaybanke was inducted onto the [[Victorian Honour Roll of Women]] in 2001 in recognition of her achievements.\n\n==Marriage and travel==\nIn 1899 Maybanke married her second husband, [[Francis Anderson (philosopher)|Sir Francis Anderson]]. Anderson was the first Professor of Philosophy at the [[University of Sydney]]. They travelled and worked together on voluntary projects, including campaigning to have women stand for local government. She was active with the National Council of Women of New South Wales, and worked closely with the University Women's Society.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://trove.nla.gov.au/people/466159 | title=Anderson, Maybanke (1845-1927) - Trove, National Library of Australia |accessdate=2011-02-26}}</ref> Maybanke died in St Germain-en-Laye, Paris on 15 April 1927.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://adb.anu.edu.au/biography/anderson-maybanke-susannah-5018/text8347 Anderson, Maybanke Susannah (1845\u20131927)] in ''Australian Dictionary of Biography''\n* [http://dictionaryofsydney.org/entry/anderson_maybanke Anderson, Maybanke] in ''Dictionary of Sydney''\n* [http://www.womenaustralia.info/leaders/biogs/WLE0601b.htm Anderson, Maybanke Susannah (1845 - 1927)] in ''The Encyclopedia of Women 